== Ingredients

Bread products are often used to hold together several different ingredients:

#list((
  sentence("ůĪ•čůĪ§ßůĪ§ďůĪ§ČůĪ•Ę", "pan li jo e soweli.", "The pizza contains meat."),
  sentence(
    "ůĪ•čůĪ§ßůĪ§ďůĪ§ČůĪ§ö",
    "pan li jo e kili.",
    "The pizza contains vegetables.",
  ),
  sentence(
    "ůĪ•čůĪ§ßůĪ§ďůĪ§ČůĪ•ł",
    "pan li jo e namako.",
    "The pizza contains condiments.",
  ),
))

But how do we put them together into a single sentence? Well, each of them is
the #emph[object] of a sentence. A sentence can have #emph[several objects]:
several #strong[ůĪ§Č e]-phrases, which simply go one after the other:

#list((
  sentence(
    "ůĪ•čůĪ§ßůĪ§ďůĪ§ČůĪ•ĘůĪ§ČůĪ§öůĪ§ČůĪ•ł",
    "pan li jo e soweli e kili e namako.",
    "The pizza contains meat, vegetables, (and) condiments.",
  ),
))

This is not special to just #strong[ůĪ§Č e]! You can combine several related ideas
into one sentence with #strong[ůĪ§ß li], #strong[ůĪ§° la], and prepositions too. For
now let's just look at #strong[ůĪ§ß li]:

#list((
  sentence(
    "ůĪ§ĎůĪ§ßůĪ§ÉůĪ§ČůĪ§Ē",
    "jan li alasa e kala.",
    "The person hunts fish. (= the person fishes).",
  ),
  sentence("ůĪ§ĎůĪ§ßůĪ•óůĪ§ČůĪ•Ü", "jan li seli e ona.", "The person cooks them."),
  sentence("ůĪ§ĎůĪ§ßůĪ§∂ůĪ§ČůĪ•Ü", "jan li moku e ona.", "The person eats them."),
  sentence(
    "ůĪ§ĎůĪ§ßůĪ§ÉůĪ§ČůĪ§ĒůĪ§ßůĪ•óůĪ§ČůĪ•ÜůĪ§ßůĪ§∂ůĪ§ČůĪ•Ü",
    "jan li alasa e kala, li seli e ona, li moku e ona.",
    "The person hunts fish, cooks them, eats them.",
  ),
))

